@(2)Say @lab{1}to the king who brightens the heart of the homeland like Utu.

@(6)Repeat to the one @lab{3}who removed oppression from the furrows, @lab{4}who
caused Tidnum to submit,^1^ who seized their (royal ) staff, @lab{5}the one
counted as their important king. @lab{7}Thus says Lugal-nesa@e, citizen of
Nippur, your servant:


@(8)My inexplicable punishment makes me glower. @lab{9}Wailing in distress
became my lot. @lab{10}In a city that has become hostile I have been moaning
like a dove, @lab{11}(but) no one took pity (on me).60 @lab{12}I am ﬁlled with restlessness, like a dog that does not know a place to rest. @lab{13}I am on alert
like a bird ﬂying from the grasp of a falcon. @lab{14}Like a garden that has
not been watered, my joy withers in fetid (decay).


@(15)The glances (of those within) the palace of my king silenced me; a
bad reputation has been attributed to me. @lab{16} ... moaning ... @lab{17}... cries
of woe ... @lab{18}Like an ox I licked my fodder (with my tongue), like a
pauper I grasped about rapaciously. @lab{19}My young ﬂedglings, dazed in
their nest, opened wide their mouths to eat some food. @lab{20}Gusty winds
from the ... desert, like ..., seize me(?) in ...


@(23)Dead but unburied,61 I am ground up like grain, ... @lab{22}My brother
(even though) he is not a stranger looked at me contemptuously.


@(21)... I hung my neck downward. @lab{24}My good has been made evil.


@(25)May the ... king, like Utu, make my appeal successful!

^1^ Var (N20): “who defeated Tidnum.”


