@translation labeled en project



@(1)Say to Enlil-massu, the one of sweet words and good advice,
melliﬂuous mouth of charming utterances. @lab{3}Repeat @lab{2}to the son who
serves his god, who respects his father and mother. @lab{7}Say for a third
time to @lab{4}the alad-spirit, the protective spirit, my precious god,
whose countenance and shape are pleasing, @lab{5}epitome of the scribal
art, @lab{6}ornament of the palace, hero of the šatam ofﬁcials, who
reinstates commands, @lab{7}who always pleases the heart of his king.


@(8 - 9)Thus says Lugal-nesa@e, the nu’eš priest of Enlil, who makes his
king laugh, son of Enlil-alsag, ummia of Nippur, your father:


@(10)When you abandoned me, you completely crushed me. @lab{11}My heart
sank, I lost the taste for food and drink.^1^ @lab{12}Your very being consumed
me, your mockery overwhelmed me. @lab{13}Your arrogance shattered me,

@(14)your insult ﬁnished me off. @lab{15}Despite my attentiveness, I have been
abandoned. @lab{16}Despite my wisdom and (good) intentions, tranquility
eluded (me). @lab{17}Despite my reverence, blood and pus ﬁlled my heart.

@(18)Making inquiries has become too troublesome.


@(19)As long as I have not gone to my (ultimate) fate, @lab{20}may your
countenance look (upon me) in accordance with Enlil’s command.

^1^ Lit: “My thirst and hunger diminished.”


