@(2)Say @lab{1}to Nintinuga, efﬁcacious steward of the Ekur, @lab{2}physician
of the homeland; @lab{7}Repeat to @lab{3}the lady whose incantations cure the
populace, @lab{4}whose spell has healed the people, @lab{5}to the
compassionate lady, reviver of persons, lover of prayer; @lab{6}to the
relenting, the merciful, who hears my petitions; @lab{8}You care for the
living and the dead, @lab{9}great healer of cripples. @lab{10–11}Thus says
Inanaka, daughter of Enlil-amah, your servant:


@(12)Having taken to bed for the second time,^1^ @lab{13}I went through much
woe and I do not know its course. @lab{14}My lady, someone built a house
for me, but I can only sit furtively. @lab{15}My acquaintances and dear ones
have abandoned me. @lab{16}I have no one who inquires about me. @lab{17}Since
it is enough for me, too much for me, @lab{18}I am truly desperate.


@(19)If it is my lady’s will, @lab{20}may she cause the asag demon that is in
my body to be torn out of my ﬂesh. @lab{21}May she stand my feet on the
path of life. @lab{22}Furthermore, as I am her servant @lab{23}(and) the courtyard
sweeper of her temple, I will serve her, @lab{24–25}(and) as soon as I am well,
I will name my lady, “healer of cripples.”

^1^ Literally: “With my being thrown to bed for the second time.”


